@Node Usage "CharConv Usage and Options"

                                                                             
  @{b}CharConv Usage@{ub}

     
     CharConv is a CLI command and can be invoked from the Shell or icon with
     tool set to Iconx. It can be used in command scripts.

     The program uses standard UNIX command templates, so typing 'CharConv -h'
     will list all the options available.

          Unix options are of the form:
          
                -<letter>               for flags
                -<letter> <value>       for parameters
                -<letter><letter>...    for flags
                
                fe. -e
                    -b thevalue
                    -tmr    
                
     Options are free form, meaning they can be typed in without taking in
     account the sequence in which they appear.
     Options are CASE SENSITIVE.
          
     See example section.
  
  @{b}Command template@{ub}

          
     Charconv [-h] [-a] [-e] [-c <char as num>] [-f <infile>] [-o <outfile>]
                        
                        
  @{b}Detail explanation of options@{ub}


        h            - display HELP.
                            
                                     
        a            - EBCDIC to ASCII conversion, so output will be [a]scii
                                
             
        e            - ASCII to EBCDIC conversion, so output will be [e]bcdic


        c            - the character (as number) to convert


        f <infile>   - the input file to convert
                            
                                     
        o <utfile>   - the output file with converted data (default = stdout).


@EndNode                        


@Node Examples "Examples"

                 
   @{b}Examples@{ub}


     This section lists some examples of usage. If you have scenarios of your
     own then send them in, to help others I'll include them here.

          - Single character conversion:

               CharConv -e -c 65

               -> 65 (ASCII) = 193 (EBCDIC)


          - File convert:

               CharConv -a -f myebcdic.txt -o myascii.txt


          - Character to file convert:

               CharConv -e -c 65 -o result.txt


          - File convert to stdout:

               CharConv -e -f myebcdic.txt
                                                  
@EndNode

          
